   function getTempRange(item) {
              let tempRange = 'ERROR';
              if (item) {
                const tempFloor = Math.floor(item / 5) * 5;
                tempRange = tempFloor + ' to ' + (tempFloor + 4);
              }
              return tempRange;
            }

            let objId, objType;
            if ('' === 'story' || '' === 'video' || '' === 'gallery') {
              objId = 'wftv/';
              objType = '';
            } else {
              const pathname = window.location.pathname;
              objType = 'index';
              if (pathname.length >= 35) {
                objId = 'wftv' + pathname.slice(pathname.length - 35, pathname.length);
              } else {
                objId = 'wftv' + pathname;
              }
            }

            window.googletag = window.googletag || {};

  <script>
   // variation of uuid algorithm with date time added
          function ppid() {
            var a = 'xyx' + Math.round(Date.now() / 1000) + 'xxxxxxxxxxxxxxyxxxxxxxxxxxx';
            return a.replace(/[xy]/g, function(c) {
              var r = Math.random() * 16 | 0, v = c == 'x' ? r : (r & 0x3 | 0x8);
              return v.toString(16);
            });
          }

        var cmgCookieString = 'uniqueCMGVisitor';
        var uniqueCMGVisitor = ppid();
        if (Cookies.get(cmgCookieString)) {
            // if the cookie exists reset it with the same value and set it to expire in 30 days
            var uniqueValue = Cookies.get(cmgCookieString);
            Cookies.set(cmgCookieString, uniqueValue, { 'expires': 30 })
        } else {
            // if it doesn't exist set it with a new value to expire in 30 days
            Cookies.set(cmgCookieString, uniqueCMGVisitor, { 'expires': 30 });
        }
  </script>

Murrow Award-winning, two-time regional Edward R. Murrow award-winning and a two-time Emmy-nominated reporter who joined the WFTV team in June 2016. Lauren comes to Orlando after working as an investigative reporter at KWCH in Wichita, Kansas.\n\nDuring Lauren’s time in Kansas, she uncovered corruption in local police departments, and her stories were nominated twice for Emmy awards. Those stories and her coverage of devastating tornadoes in Kansas and Oklahoma won several Kansas Association of Broadcasters awards.\n\nHer National Murrow Award for \"investigating reporter\" came from an investigation in which she uncovered a police chief's history of being fired several times and hiring officers with similar backgrounds. It revealed a problem with the vetting process of small town police departments hiring officers who had a history of being fired from other departments. The second Regional Murrow tells a story of a former FBI agent who was the first to identify Timothy McVeigh as the Oklahoma City bombing suspect.\n\nBefore Wichita, Lauren worked in Topeka, Kansas as the main anchor and a reporter at KSNT/KTKA. Her reports on northeast Kansas parents who were the first to get their adopted children out of Haiti after the 2010 earthquake gained national attention. Lauren introduced the family to the country live on CNN’s Headline News.\n\nLauren is a native Oklahoman who enjoys living in the Sunshine State and being close to the beach. She’s a diehard University of Oklahoma Sooner fan and loves the Oklahoma City Thunder. Lauren finished her first half-marathon in 2015 and has taken up boxing since moving to Florida. winter storms to Winter Park, I grew up in Wisconsin but recently moved to Orlando for the wonderful winter weather!   \n\nDon’t get me wrong, I love all exciting weather.  I forecasted thunderstorms, snowstorms, ice storms and heat waves in the Central Plains for seven years. \n\nFrom Sioux City, Iowa; Tulsa & Kansas City, these gigs in tornado alley will serve as good experience tracking the many Florida thunderstorms. \n\nBut I didn’t start out as a meteorologist, I started as a farmer.  I grew up on a family dairy farm.  My 10 brothers and sisters and I milked cows all winter long, even as temperatures dropped below zero and snowstorms dropped multiple feet of snow.\n\nMy first job out of college was not in meteorology, either.  It was engineering.  Geotechnical engineering.  I worked at a firm that designed foundations for New York City skyscrapers. \n\nOne project sent me trekking deep below the streets of Manhattan to monitor the construction vibrations on the Subway tracks.  Another had me approving pits for the construction of the foundation for a 44-story building. \n\nIt was a fascinating job, but somewhere in my second year, I received an offer to attend UCLA’s grad school.  This is where I entered the weather workforce.\n\nIt was the Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences department at UCLA. I worked as a graduate student researcher studying two major storms: Hurricane Andrew and the 1993 Storm of the Century.  My job was to manipulate the computer models to see how likely it was to make these storms even stronger, all while earning my Master’s Degree.\n\nAnd the icing on the cake?  My UCLA diploma has the signature of then-Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger!\n\nSince I’m new to the area, I’ll be familiarizing myself with central Florida. I’ll be out and about visiting many of the local communities, so if you see me in your neighborhood, give me a friendly “hello”.\n\nAnd yes, growing up in Wisconsin, I do love snow…but I may love “no She joined the team in April 2018.\n\nBefore that, Megan was a reporter for KOAT in Albuquerque, New Mexico. While there, her reporting of a statewide behavioral health and addiction clinic got the attention of the State Attorney General’s Office, which later investigated the clinic for Medicaid fraud. She also exposed a paramilitary religious sect in which various members were accused of child abuse. One of its leaders was just sentenced to 72 years in prison. During the investigation, 11 children were rescued from the secluded compound.\n\nMegan was born and raised in New York City, where she attended New York University then got her first news job at NY1. She started as an intern, then was hired as a photographer, began to field produce - and also worked on the assignment desk to vet stories and cultivate sources. NY1’s sister station in Albany, New York, then hired her as a reporter. She appeared on CNN for her reporting of Tropical Storm Irene, which severely damaged several upstate New York towns.\n\nOver the years, Megan has been honored with several nominations and awards, including an Edward R. Murrow award for team coverage of a school shooting in Aztec, New Mexico. She also received a New Mexico Broadcasting award for her continued coverage of the state’s opioid crisis. \n\nWhen not researching a story, Megan is usually planning a trip somewhere! She loves to explore new places both near and far. When home, you’ll likely see her with her dog, Duke – she rescued him in 2016.\n\nHave a story idea or just want to say hi? winter storms to Winter Park, I grew up in Wisconsin but recently moved to Orlando for the wonderful winter weather!   \n\nDon’t get me wrong, I love all exciting weather.  I forecasted thunderstorms, snowstorms, ice storms and heat waves in the Central Plains for seven years. \n\nFrom Sioux City, Iowa; Tulsa & Kansas City, these gigs in tornado alley will serve as good experience tracking the many Florida thunderstorms. \n\nBut I didn’t start out as a meteorologist, I started as a farmer. My 10 brothers and sisters and I milked cows all winter long, even as temperatures dropped below zero and snowstorms dropped multiple feet of snow.\n\nMy first job out of college was not in meteorology, either.  It was engineering.  Geotechnical engineering.  I worked at a firm that designed foundations for New York City skyscrapers. \n\nOne project sent me trekking deep below the streets of Manhattan to monitor the construction vibrations on the Subway tracks.  Another had me approving pits for the construction of the foundation for a 44-story building. \n\nIt was a fascinating job, but somewhere in my second year, I received an offer to attend UCLA’s grad school.  This is where I entered the weather workforce.\n\nIt was the Atmospheric and Oceanic Sciences department at UCLA. I worked as a graduate student researcher studying two major storms: Hurricane Andrew and the 1993 Storm of the Century. My UCLA diploma has the signature of then-Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger!\n\nSince I’m new to the area, I’ll be familiarizing myself with central Florida.
